<p>
<seg id=1> Now news from China. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=2> The Chinese government recently detained several political dissidents to prevent the meeting of Chinese democratic party members in Zhejiang and Shanghai. </seg>
<seg id=3> Here is VOA's report in Chinese, Qing Yue reporting. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> According to the Hong Kong-based intelligence center of human rights and democracy in China, policemen in Hangzhou took two democratic party members, Zhu Zhengming and Mao Qingxiang, from their homes Friday afternoon. </seg>
<seg id=5> At present, there is no information about the two men. </seg>
<seg id=6> Before this, policemen had detained another four members related to the democratic party of China: Yao Zhenxian, Li Guotao, Wu Yilong and Wang Rongqing. </seg>
<seg id=7> According to the intelligence center, about 20 democratic party members in Zhejiang and Shanghai planned to hold their first meeting in a restaurant in Hangzhou Friday afternoon. </seg>
<seg id=8> The police carried out the detentions to deter the gathering. </seg>
<seg id=9> In addition, policemen in other areas of Zhejiang also warned other active participants in democratic movements not to leave their homes or they might be detained. </seg>
<seg id=10> The Chinese government regards opponent parties as illegal organizations and detained and examined tens of supporters and active participants. </seg>
<seg id=11> But in most cases they are quickly released. </seg>
<seg id=12> Associated Press, Reuters and French News Agence reported the information recently released by the center. </seg>
</p>
